We consider the case of $\Delta_j\gg g_j$ with $\Delta_j =\omega_{c,j}-\omega_q$. Then, the qubit-TLR interaction, represented by the last term of $H_S$, only acts perturbatively in this dispersive regime. To get resonate interaction between the selected TLR and the transmon qubit, the qubit is biased by an ac magnetic flux, which will introduce periodical modulation \cite{Strand2013} of the qubit transition frequency in the form of
\begin{eqnarray}\label{twotone}
\omega_q(t)=\omega_q+ \sum_{j=1}^2 \varepsilon_j \sin (\nu_j t-\phi_j).
\end{eqnarray}
As the transmon is placed in the middle of the two TLRs, we can drive the transmon by applying a well-controlled, two-tone microwave drive. For the presented experiments \cite{Fink2009, Steffen2013}, the transmon can tune to idle state transition frequency $\omega_q$ with miniature superconducting coils mounted underneath the chip.
This modulation may effectively turn the qubit's sideband on resonance with the cavity frequency. To see this, we move to the rotating frame defined by
\begin{eqnarray}
U=\exp\left[\sum_{j=1}^{2} i\sigma^z  {\alpha_j \over 2 } \cos (\nu_j t-\phi_j)-i \omega_{c,j} a_j^\dag a_j t -i{\omega_q \over 2} \sigma^z t \right] \notag
\end{eqnarray}
with $\alpha_j=\varepsilon_j / \nu_j$. Then, the transformed Hamiltonian reads
\begin{eqnarray}\label{trans}
H'(t)&=&\left(g_1 a_1^\dag \sigma^- e^{i \Delta_1 t} + g_2 a_2^\dag \sigma^- e^{i \Delta_2 t}\right) \\ \notag
&\times& \prod_{j=1}^2 \sum_{m=-\infty}^\infty  i^m J_m(\alpha_j) e^{i m(\nu_j t -\phi_j)} +\text{H.c.},
\end{eqnarray}
where $J_m(\alpha_j)$ being Bessel functions of the first kind. Under the condition of $\nu_j=\Delta_j$, the effective resonate interaction will be
\begin{eqnarray}  \label{eff}
H_\text{eff} &=& g[J_1(\alpha_1) a_1^\dag \sigma^-  + J_0(\alpha_1) a_2^\dag \sigma^- e^{i\phi'}+ \text{H.c.}],
\end{eqnarray}
where $\phi'=\phi_2-\phi_1$, and $g=g'J$ with $g_1=g_2=g'$ and $J_0(\alpha_2)=J_1(\alpha_2)=J$, i.e., $\alpha_2 \simeq 1.4347$. In this way, we have a full control over the coupling strength by varying the external driven ac magnetic flux, i.e., the amplitude $\varepsilon_1$ and phase $\phi_1$. Moreover, we have  applied the rotating wave approximation and the omitted terms has a smallest oscillating frequency of $\Delta=|\Delta_2-\Delta_1|$, i.e.,
\begin{eqnarray} \label{osc}
H_1'=g\left[J_1(\alpha_1) a_2^\dag \sigma^- e^{i\Delta t} + J_0(\alpha_1) a_1^\dag \sigma^- e^{-i\Delta t+\phi'} + \text{H.c.}\right].\notag\\
\end{eqnarray}




